# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: u-boot-bootloader
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:u-boot-bootloader/board-support-package] The board support package is usually provided by the SoC manufacturer (such as Qualcomm), and may be modified by the OEM.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/board-support-package] Third-party hardware developers who wish to support a given embedded operating system must create a BSP that allows that embedded operating system to run on their platform.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/board-support-package] In most cases, the embedded operating system image—containing the BSP, software license, and hardware support—is bundled together by the hardware vendor.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/board-support-package] BSPs are typically customizable, allowing the user to specify which drivers and routines should be included in the build based on their selection of hardware and software options.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/board-support-package] For instance, a particular single-board computer might be paired with several peripheral chips; in that case the BSP might include drivers for peripheral chips supported; when building the BSP image the user would specify which peripheral drivers to include based on their choice of hardware.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/board-support-package] Some suppliers also provide a root file system, a toolchain for building programs to run on the embedded system, and utilities to configure the device (while running) along with the BSP.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/board-support-package] Many embedded operating system providers provide template BSP's, developer assistance, and test suites to aid BSP developers to set up an embedded operating system on a new hardware platform.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/board-support-package] The term *BSP* has been in use since 1981 when Hunter & Ready, the developers of the Versatile Real-Time Executive (VRTX), first coined the term to describe the hardware-dependent software needed to run VRTX on a specific hardware platform.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/board-support-package] Since the 1980s, it has been in wide use throughout the industry.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/board-support-package] Virtually all RTOS providers now use the term BSP.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/board-support-package] In modern systems, the term has been extended to refer to packages that only deal with one processor, not the whole motherboard.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] This may be done by hardware or firmware in the CPU, or by a separate processor in the computer system.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] On some systems, a power-on reset (POR) does not initiate booting, and the operator must initiate booting after POR completes.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] IBM uses the term **Initial Program Load** (**IPL**) on some product lines.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Restarting a computer is also called *rebooting*, which can be "hard", e.g., after electrical power to the CPU is switched from off to on, or "soft", where the power is not cut.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] On some systems, a soft boot may optionally clear RAM to zero.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Both hard and soft booting can be initiated by hardware, such as a button press, or by a software command.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Booting is complete when the operative runtime system, typically the operating system and some applications, is attained.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The process of returning a computer from a state of sleep (suspension) does not involve booting; however, restoring it from a state of hibernation does.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Minimally, some embedded systems do not require a noticeable boot sequence to begin functioning, and when turned on, may simply run operational programs that are stored in read-only memory (ROM).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] All computing systems are state machines, and a reboot may be the only method to return to a designated zero-state from an unintended, locked state.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] In addition to loading an operating system or stand-alone utility, the boot process can also load a storage dump program for diagnosing problems in an operating system.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The earliest known recorded use of "boot" as the shortened form for "bootstrap" is 1975.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] There are many different methods available to load a short initial program into a computer.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] These methods range from simple, physical input to removable media that can hold more complex programs.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Early computers in the 1940s and 1950s were one-of-a-kind engineering efforts that could take weeks to program, and program loading was one of many problems that had to be solved.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] An early computer, ENIAC, had no program stored in memory but was set up for each problem by a configuration of interconnecting cables.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Bootstrapping did not apply to ENIAC, whose hardware configuration was ready for solving problems as soon as power was applied.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The EDSAC system, the second stored-program computer to be built, used stepping switches to transfer a fixed program into memory when its start button was pressed.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The program stored on this device, which David Wheeler completed in late 1948, loaded further instructions from punched tape and then executed them.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The first programmable computers for commercial sale, such as the UNIVAC I and the IBM 701 included features to make their operation simpler.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] They typically included instructions that performed a complete input or output operation.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The same hardware logic could be used to load the contents of a punch card (the most typical ones) or other input media, such as a magnetic drum or magnetic tape, that contained a bootstrap program by pressing a single button.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] This booting concept was called a variety of names for IBM computers of the 1950s and early 1960s, but IBM used the term "Initial Program Load" with the IBM 7030 Stretch and later used it for their mainframe lines, starting with the System/360 in 1964.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The IBM 701 computer (1952–1956) had a "Load" button that initiated reading of the first 36-bit word into main memory from a punched card in a card reader, a magnetic tape in a tape drive, or a magnetic drum unit, depending on the position of the Load Selector switch.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The left 18-bit half-word was then executed as an instruction, which usually read additional words into memory.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The loaded boot program was then executed, which, in turn, loaded a larger program from that medium into memory without further help from the human operator.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The IBM 704, IBM 7090, and IBM 7094 had similar mechanisms, but with different load buttons for different devices.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The term "boot" has been used in this sense since at least 1958.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Other IBM computers of that era had similar features.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] For example, the IBM 1401 system (1959) used a card reader to load a program from a punched card.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The 80 characters stored in the punched card were read into memory locations 001 to 080, then the computer would branch to memory location 001 to read its first stored instruction.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] This instruction was always the same: move the information in these first 80 memory locations to an assembly area where the information in punched cards 2, 3, 4, and so on, could be combined to form the stored program.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Once this information was moved to the assembly area, the machine would branch to an instruction in location 080 (read a card) and the next card would be read and its information processed.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Another example was the IBM 650 (1953), a decimal machine, which had a group of ten 10-position switches on its operator panel that were addressable as a memory word (address 8000) and could be executed as an instruction.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Thus, setting the switches to 7004000400 and pressing the appropriate button would read the first card in the card reader into memory (op code 70), starting at address 400 and then jump to 400 to begin executing the program on that card.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] IBM's competitors also offered single-button program load.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] A noteworthy variation of this is found on the Burroughs B1700, where there is neither a boot ROM nor a hardwired IPL operation.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Instead, after the system is reset, it reads and executes microinstructions sequentially from a cassette tape drive mounted on the front panel; this sets up a boot loader in RAM, which is then executed.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] However, since this makes few assumptions about the system it can equally well be used to load diagnostic (Maintenance Test Routine) tapes which display an intelligible code on the front panel even in cases of gross CPU failure.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] In the IBM System/360 and its successors, including the current z/Architecture machines, the boot process is known as *Initial Program Load* (IPL).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] IBM coined this term for the 7030 (Stretch), revived it for the design of the System/360, and continues to use it in those environments today.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] In the System/360 processors, an IPL is initiated by the computer operator by selecting the three hexadecimal digit device address (CUU; C=I/O Channel address, UU=Control unit and Device address) followed by pressing the *LOAD* button.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] On the high end System/360 models, most System/370 and some later systems, the functions of the switches and the LOAD button are simulated using selectable areas on the screen of a graphics console, often an IBM 2250-like device or an IBM 3270-like device.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] For example, on the System/370 Model 158, the keyboard sequence 0-7-X (zero, seven and X, in that order) results in an IPL from the device address that was keyed into the input area.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The Amdahl 470V/6 and related CPUs supported four hexadecimal digits on those CPUs that had the optional second channel unit installed, for a total of 32 channels.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Later, IBM would also support more than 16 channels.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The IPL function in the System/360 and its successors prior to IBM Z, and its compatibles, such as Amdahl's, reads 24 bytes from an operator-specified device into main storage starting at real address zero.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The second and third groups of eight bytes are treated as Channel Command Words (CCWs) to continue loading the startup program (the first CCW is always simulated by the CPU and consists of a Read IPL command, 02h, with command chaining and suppress incorrect length indication being enforced).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] When the I/O channel commands are complete, the first group of eight bytes is then loaded into the processor's Program Status Word (PSW) and the startup program begins execution at the location designated by that PSW.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] IBM introduced some evolutionary changes in the IPL process, changing some details for System/370 Extended Architecture (S/370-XA) and later, and adding a new type of IPL for z/Architecture.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Minicomputers, starting with the Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-5 and PDP-8 (1965) simplified design by using the CPU to assist input and output operations.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] This saved cost but made booting more complicated than pressing a single button.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Minicomputers typically had some way to *toggle in* short programs by manipulating an array of switches on the front panel.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Since the early minicomputers used magnetic-core memory, which did not lose its information when power was off, these bootstrap loaders would remain in place unless they were erased.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Erasure sometimes happened accidentally when a program bug caused a loop that overwrote all of memory.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Other minicomputers with such simple form of booting include Hewlett-Packard's HP 2100 series (mid-1960s), the original Data General Nova (1969), and DEC's PDP-4 (1962) and PDP-11 (1970).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] As the I/O operations needed to cause a read operation on a minicomputer I/O device were typically different for different device controllers, different bootstrap programs were needed for different devices.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] DEC later added, in 1971, an optional diode matrix read-only memory for the PDP-11 that stored a bootstrap program of up to 32 words (64 bytes).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] It consisted of a printed circuit card, the M792, that plugged into the Unibus and held a 32 by 16 array of semiconductor diodes.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] With all 512 diodes in place, the memory contained all "one" bits; the card was programmed by cutting off each diode whose bit was to be "zero".
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] DEC also sold versions of the card, the BM792-Yx series, pre-programmed for many standard input devices by simply omitting the unneeded diodes.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Following the older approach, the earlier PDP-1 has a hardware loader, such that an operator needs only push the *load* switch to instruct the paper tape reader to load a program directly into core memory.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The PDP-7, PDP-9, and PDP-15 successors to the PDP-4 have an added Read-In button to read a program in from paper tape and jump to it.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The Data General Supernova used front panel switches to cause the computer to automatically load instructions into memory from a device specified by the front panel's data switches, and then jump to loaded code.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] In a minicomputer with a paper tape reader, the first program to run in the boot process, the boot loader, would read into core memory either the second-stage boot loader (often called a *Binary Loader*) that could read paper tape with checksum or the operating system from an outside storage medium.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] A related example is based on a loader for a Nicolet Instrument Corporation minicomputer of the 1970s, using the paper tape reader-punch unit on a Teletype Model 33 ASR teleprinter.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The bytes of its second-stage loader are read from paper tape in reverse order.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The length of the second stage loader is such that the final byte overwrites location 7.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] After the instruction in location 6 executes, location 7 starts the second stage loader executing.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The second stage loader then waits for the much longer tape containing the operating system to be placed in the tape reader.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The difference between the boot loader and second stage loader is the addition of checking code to trap paper tape read errors, a frequent occurrence with relatively low-cost, "part-time-duty" hardware, such as the Teletype Model 33 ASR.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The earliest microcomputers, such as the Altair 8800 (released first in 1975) and an even earlier, similar machine (based on the Intel 8008 CPU) had no bootstrapping hardware as such.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] When powered up, the CPU would see memory that would contain random data.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The front panels of these machines carried toggle switches for entering addresses and data, one switch per bit of the computer memory word and address bus.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Simple additions to the hardware permitted one memory location at a time to be loaded from those switches to store bootstrap code.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Meanwhile, the CPU was kept from attempting to execute memory content.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Once correctly loaded, the CPU was enabled to execute the bootstrapping code.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] This process, similar to that used for several earlier minicomputers, was tedious and had to be error-free.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The introduction of integrated circuit read-only memory (ROM), with its many variants, including mask-programmed ROMs, programmable ROMs (PROM), erasable programmable ROMs (EPROM), and flash memory, reduced the physical size and cost of ROM.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] This allowed firmware boot programs to be included as part of the computer.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The Data General Nova 1200 (1970) and Nova 800 (1971) had a program load switch that, in combination with options that provided two ROM chips, loaded a program into main memory from those ROM chips and jumped to it.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Digital Equipment Corporation introduced the integrated-circuit-ROM-based BM873 (1974), M9301 (1977), M9312 (1978), REV11-A and REV11-C, MRV11-C, and MRV11-D ROM memories, all usable as bootstrap ROMs.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] An Italian telephone switching computer, called "Gruppi Speciali", patented in 1975 by Alberto Ciaramella, a researcher at CSELT, included an (external) ROM.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Gruppi Speciali was, starting from 1975, a fully single-button machine booting into the operating system from a ROM memory composed of semiconductors, not ferrite cores.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Although the ROM device was not natively embedded in the computer of Gruppi Speciali, due to the design of the machine, it also allowed the single-button ROM booting in machines not designed for that (therefore, this "bootstrap device" was architecture-independent), e.g., the PDP-11.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Storing the state of the machine after the switch-off was also in place, which was another critical feature in the telephone switching contest.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Some minicomputers and superminicomputers include a separate console processor that bootstraps the main processor.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The PDP-11/44 had an Intel 8085 as a console processor; the VAX-11/780, the first member of Digital's VAX line of 32-bit superminicomputers, had an LSI-11-based console processor, and the VAX-11/730 had an 8085-based console processor.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] These console processors could boot the main processor from various storage devices.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Some other superminicomputers, such as the VAX-11/750, implement console functions, including the first stage of booting, in CPU microcode.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] A system built using that microprocessor will have the permanent ROM occupying these special locations so that the system always begins operating without operator assistance.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] For example, Intel x86 processors always start by running the instructions beginning at F000:FFF0, while for the MOS 6502 processor, initialization begins by reading a two-byte vector address at $FFFD (MS byte) and $FFFC (LS byte) and jumping to that location to run the bootstrap code.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Apple Computer's first computer, the Apple 1, introduced in 1976, featured PROM chips that eliminated the need for a front panel for the boot process (as was the case with the Altair 8800) in a commercial computer.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Due to the expense of read-only memory at the time, the Apple II booted its disk operating systems using a series of very small incremental steps, each passing control onward to the next phase of the gradually more complex boot process.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Because so little of the disk operating system relied on ROM, the hardware was also extremely flexible and supported a wide range of customized disk copy protection mechanisms.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Some operating systems, most notably pre-1995 Macintosh systems from Apple, are so closely interwoven with their hardware that it is impossible to natively boot an operating system other than the standard one.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] This is the opposite extreme of the scenario using switches mentioned above; it is highly inflexible but relatively error-proof and foolproof as long as all hardware is working normally.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] A common solution in such situations is to design a boot loader that works as a program belonging to the standard OS that hijacks the system and loads the alternative OS.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] This technique was used by Apple for its A/UX Unix implementation and copied by various freeware operating systems and BeOS Personal Edition 5.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Some machines, like the Atari ST microcomputer, were "instant-on", with the operating system executing from a ROM.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Retrieval of the OS from secondary or tertiary store was thus eliminated as one of the characteristic operations for bootstrapping.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] To allow system customizations, accessories, and other support software to be loaded automatically, the Atari's floppy drive was read for additional components during the boot process.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] There was a timeout delay that provided time to manually insert a floppy as the system searched for the extra components.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] This could be avoided by inserting a blank disk.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The IBM Personal Computer included ROM-based firmware called the BIOS; one of the functions of that firmware was to perform a power-on self test when the machine was powered up, and then to read software from a boot device and execute it.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Firmware compatible with the BIOS on the IBM Personal Computer is used in IBM PC compatible computers.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The UEFI was developed by Intel, originally for Itanium-based machines, and later also used as an alternative to the BIOS in x86-based machines, including Apple Macs using Intel processors.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Unix workstations originally had vendor-specific ROM-based firmware.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Sun Microsystems later developed OpenBoot, later known as Open Firmware, which incorporated a Forth interpreter, with much of the firmware being written in Forth.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] It was standardized by the IEEE as IEEE standard 1275-1994; firmware that implements that standard was used in PowerPC-based Macs and some other PowerPC-based machines, as well as Sun's own SPARC-based computers.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The Advanced RISC Computing specification defined another firmware standard, which was implemented on some MIPS-based and Alpha-based machines and the SGI Visual Workstation x86-based workstations.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] When a computer is turned off, its software‍—‌including operating systems, application code, and data‍—‌remains stored on non-volatile memory.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] When the computer is powered on, it typically does not have an operating system or its loader in random-access memory (RAM).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The small program that starts this sequence is known as a *bootstrap loader*, *bootstrap* or *boot loader*.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Often, multiple-stage boot loaders are used, during which several programs of increasing complexity load one after the other in a process of chain loading.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Some earlier computer systems, upon receiving a boot signal from a human operator or a peripheral device, may load a very small number of fixed instructions into memory at a specific location, initialize at least one CPU, and then point the CPU to the instructions and start their execution.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] These instructions typically start an input operation from some peripheral device (which may be switch-selectable by the operator).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Smaller computers often use less flexible but more automatic boot loader mechanisms to ensure that the computer starts quickly and with a predetermined software configuration.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] In many desktop computers, for example, the bootstrapping process begins with the CPU executing software contained in ROM (for example, the BIOS of an IBM PC) at a predefined address (some CPUs, including the Intel x86 series are designed to execute this software after reset without outside help).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] This software contains rudimentary functionality to search for devices eligible to participate in booting, and load a small program from a special section (most commonly the boot sector) of the most promising device, typically starting at a fixed entry point such as the start of the sector.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] On systems with those constraints, the first program loaded into RAM may not be sufficiently large to load the operating system and, instead, must load another, larger program.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The first program loaded into RAM is called a first-stage boot loader, and the program it loads is called a second-stage boot loader.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] On many embedded CPUs, the CPU built-in boot ROM, sometimes called the zero-stage boot loader, can find and load first-stage boot loaders.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Examples of first-stage (hardware initialization stage) boot loaders include BIOS, UEFI, coreboot, Libreboot and Das U-Boot.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] On the IBM PC, the boot loader in the Master Boot Record (MBR) and the Partition Boot Record (PBR) was coded to require at least 32 KB (later expanded to 64 KB) of system memory and only use instructions supported by the original 8088/8086 processors.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The second-stage boot loader does not need drivers for its own operation, but may instead use generic storage access methods provided by system firmware such as the BIOS, UEFI or Open Firmware, though typically with restricted hardware functionality and lower performance.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Many boot loaders (like GNU GRUB, rEFInd, Windows's BOOTMGR, Syslinux, and Windows NT/2000/XP's NTLDR) can be configured to give the user multiple booting choices.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Some boot loaders can also load other boot loaders; for example, GRUB loads BOOTMGR instead of loading Windows directly.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Usually, a default choice is preselected with a time delay during which a user can press a key to change the choice; after this delay, the default choice is automatically run so normal booting can occur without interaction.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The boot process can be considered complete when the computer is ready to interact with the user, or the operating system is capable of running system programs or application programs.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Some boot loaders, such as Das U-Boot and iBoot, include both first- and second-stage boot functions.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Many embedded systems must boot immediately.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] For example, waiting a minute for a digital television or a GPS navigation device to start is generally unacceptable.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Therefore, such devices have software systems in ROM or flash memory so the device can begin functioning immediately; little or no loading is necessary, because the loading can be precomputed and stored on the ROM when the device is made.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Large and complex systems may have boot procedures that proceed in multiple phases until finally the operating system and other programs are loaded and ready to execute.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Because operating systems are designed as if they never start or stop, a boot loader might load the operating system, configure itself as a mere process within that system, and then irrevocably transfer control to the operating system.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The boot loader then terminates normally as any other process would.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Most computers are also capable of booting over a computer network.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] In this scenario, the operating system is stored on the disk of a server, and certain parts of it are transferred to the client using a simple protocol such as the Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] After these parts have been transferred, the operating system takes over control of the booting process.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] As with the second-stage boot loader, network booting begins by using generic network access methods provided by the network interface's boot ROM, which typically contains a Preboot Execution Environment (PXE) image.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] No drivers are required, but the system functionality is limited until the operating system kernel and drivers are transferred and started.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] As a result, once the ROM-based booting has completed it is entirely possible to network boot into an operating system that itself does not have the ability to use the network interface.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The boot device is the storage device from which the operating system is loaded.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Older, less common BIOS-bootable devices include floppy disk drives, Zip drives, and LS-120 drives.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] IBM-compatible PCs are examples that use horizontal integrated hardware and UEFI/BIOS firmware.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Typically, the system firmware (UEFI or BIOS) will allow the user to configure a *boot order*.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] If the boot order is set to "first, the DVD drive; second, the hard disk drive", then the firmware will try to boot from the DVD drive, and if this fails (e.g., because there is no DVD in the drive), it will try to boot from the local hard disk drive.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] For example, on a PC with Windows installed on the hard drive, the user could set the boot order to the one given above, and then insert a Linux Live CD in order to try out Linux without having to install an operating system onto the hard drive.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] This is an example of dual booting, in which the user chooses which operating system to start after the computer has performed its power-on self-test (POST).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Several devices are available that enable the user to *quick-boot* into what is usually a variant of Linux for various simple tasks such as Internet access; examples are Splashtop and Latitude ON.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] This memory location typically contains a jump instruction that transfers execution to the location of the firmware (UEFI or BIOS) start-up program.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] This program runs a power-on self-test (POST) to check and initialize required devices such as main memory (DRAM), the PCI bus and the PCI devices (including running embedded option ROMs).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] One of the most involved steps is setting up DRAM over SPD, further complicated by the fact that, at this point, memory is very limited.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] After initializing required hardware, the firmware (UEFI or BIOS) goes through a pre-configured list of non-volatile storage devices ("boot device sequence") until it finds one that is bootable.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Once the BIOS has found a bootable device it loads the boot sector to linear address 7C00h (usually segment:offset 0000h:7C00h, but some BIOSes erroneously use 07C0h:0000h) and transfers execution to the boot code.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] In the case of a hard disk, this is referred to as the Master Boot Record (MBR).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The conventional MBR code checks the MBR's partition table for a partition set as *bootable* (the one with *active* flag set).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] If an active partition is found, the MBR code loads the boot sector code from that partition, known as Volume Boot Record (VBR), and executes it.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The MBR boot code is often operating-system specific.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The boot sector code is the first-stage boot loader.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The boot loader was then able to load the first three sectors of the file into memory, which happened to contain another embedded boot loader able to load the remainder of the file into memory.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] When Microsoft added LBA and FAT32 support, they even switched to a boot loader reaching over *two* physical sectors and using 386 instructions for size reasons.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] At the same time, other vendors managed to squeeze much more functionality into a single boot sector without relaxing the original constraints on only minimal available memory (32 KB) and processor support (8088/8086).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] For example, DR-DOS boot sectors are able to locate the boot file in the FAT12, FAT16 and FAT32 file system, and load it into memory as a whole via CHS or LBA, even if the file is not stored in a fixed location and in consecutive sectors.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The VBR is often OS-specific; however, its main function is to load and execute the operating system boot loader file (such as `bootmgr` or `ntldr`), which is the second-stage boot loader, from an active partition.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Then the boot loader loads the OS kernel from the storage device.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] If there is no active partition, or the active partition's boot sector is invalid, the MBR may load a secondary boot loader which will select a partition (often via user input) and load its boot sector, which usually loads the corresponding operating system kernel.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] In some cases, the MBR may also attempt to load secondary boot loaders before trying to boot the active partition.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] If all else fails, it should issue an INT 18h BIOS interrupt call (followed by an INT 19h just in case INT 18h would return) in order to give back control to the BIOS, which would then attempt to boot off other devices, attempt a remote boot via network.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Many modern systems (Intel Macs and newer PCs) use UEFI.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Unlike BIOS, UEFI (not **Legacy boot** via CSM) does not rely on boot sectors, UEFI system loads the boot loader (**EFI application** file in USB disk or in the EFI System Partition) directly, and the OS kernel is loaded by the boot loader.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] It is difficult to hardwire all the required logic for handling such devices, so an integrated boot ROM is used instead in such scenarios.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Also, a boot ROM may be able to load a boot loader or diagnostic program via serial interfaces like UART, SPI, USB and so on.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] This feature is often used for system recovery purposes, or it could also be used for initial non-volatile memory programming when there is no software available in the non-volatile memory yet.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Many modern microcontrollers (e.g., flash memory controller on USB flash drives) have firmware ROM integrated directly into their silicon.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Some embedded system designs may also include an intermediary boot sequence step.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] For example, Das U-Boot may be split into two stages: the platform would load a small SPL (Secondary Program Loader), which is a stripped-down version of U-Boot, and the SPL would do some initial hardware configuration (e.g.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] DRAM initialization using CPU cache as RAM) and load the larger, fully featured version of U-Boot.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Such embedded systems may used highly customized and vertical integrated hardware and software, and their boot programs may be simpler.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Some CPUs and SoCs may not use CPU cache as RAM on boot process, they use an integrated boot processor to do some hardware configuration to reduce cost.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] It is also possible to take control of a system by using a hardware debug interface such as JTAG.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Such an interface may be used to write the boot loader program into bootable non-volatile memory (e.g. flash) by instructing the processor core to perform the necessary actions to program non-volatile memory.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Alternatively, the debug interface may be used to upload some diagnostic or boot code into RAM, and then to start the processor core and instruct it to execute the uploaded code.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] This allows, for example, the recovery of embedded systems where no software remains on any supported boot device, and where the processor does not have any integrated boot ROM.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] JTAG is a standard and popular interface; many CPUs, microcontrollers and other devices are manufactured with JTAG interfaces (as of 2009).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Some microcontrollers provide special hardware interfaces that cannot be used to take arbitrary control of a system or directly run code, but instead allow the insertion of boot code into bootable non-volatile memory (like flash memory) via simple protocols.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Then, at the manufacturing phase, such interfaces are used to inject boot code (and possibly other code) into non-volatile memory.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] After system reset, the microcontroller begins to execute code programmed into its non-volatile memory, just like usual processors use ROMs for booting.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Most notably, this technique is used by Atmel AVR microcontrollers, and by others as well.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] In many cases, such interfaces are implemented by hardwired logic.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] In other cases, such interfaces could be created by software running in integrated on-chip boot ROM from GPIO pins.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Most DSPs have a serial mode boot and a parallel mode boot, such as the host port interface (HPI boot).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] In the case of DSPs, there is often a second microprocessor or microcontroller present in the system design, and this is responsible for overall system behavior, interrupt handling, dealing with external events, user interface, etc., while the DSP is dedicated to signal processing tasks only.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] In such systems, the DSP could be booted by another processor, which is sometimes referred as the *host processor* (giving name to a Host Port).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Such a processor is also sometimes referred to as the *master*, since it usually boots first from its own memories and then controls overall system behavior, including booting of the DSP, and then further controls the DSP's behavior.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The DSP often lacks its own boot memories and relies on the host processor to supply the required code instead.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The most notable systems with such a design are cell phones, modems, audio and video players and so on, where a DSP and a CPU/microcontroller coexist.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Many FPGA chips load their configuration from an external configuration ROM, typically a serial EEPROM, on power-up.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Various measures have been implemented that enhance the security of the booting process.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Some of them are made mandatory, others can be disabled or enabled by the end user.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Traditionally, booting did not involve the use of cryptography.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The security can be bypassed by unlocking the boot loader, which might or might not be approved by the manufacturer.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Modern boot loaders make use of concurrency, meaning they can run multiple processor cores and threads at the same time, which adds extra layers of complexity to secure booting.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Matthew Garrett argued that booting security serves a legitimate goal, but in doing so chooses defaults that are hostile to users.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] The system might exhibit its erroneous state in, for example, an explicit bootloop or a blue screen of death, before recovery is indicated.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Detection of an erroneous state may require a distributed event store and stream-processing platform for real-time operation of a distributed system.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] An erroneous state can trigger bootloops; this state can be caused by misconfiguration from previously known-good operations.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Recovery attempts from that erroneous state then enter a reboot, in an attempt to return to a known-good state.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] In Windows OS operations, for example, the recovery procedure was to reboot three times, the reboots needed to return to a usable menu.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] Recovery might be specified via Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML), which can also implement Single sign-on (SSO) for some applications; in the zero trust security model, identification, authorization, and authentication are separable concerns in an SSO session.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/booting] When recovery of a site is indicated (viz., a blue screen of death is displayed on an airport terminal screen) personal site visits might be required to remediate the situation.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] A **bootloader**, also spelled as **boot loader** or called **bootstrap loader**, is a computer program that is responsible for booting a computer and booting an operating system.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] If it also provides an interactive menu with multiple boot choices then it is often called a **boot manager**.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] Examples of first-stage bootloaders include BIOS, UEFI, coreboot, Libreboot, and Das U-Boot.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] It initializes hardware devices such as CPU, motherboard, memory, storage and other I/O devices.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] Second-stage boot loaders, such as GNU GRUB, rEFInd, BOOTMGR, Syslinux, and NTLDR, are not themselves operating systems, but are able to load an operating system properly and transfer execution to it; the operating system subsequently initializes itself and may load extra device drivers.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] Second-stage implementations can include interactive user interfaces, allowing boot option selection and parameter modification.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] They handle kernel loading, including processing of initrd/initramfs images, and can pass boot parameters to the kernel.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] Many implement modular designs supporting loadable modules for additional functionality.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] They may also handle compression, cryptographic verification, and chain-loading of other bootloaders.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] In x86 computers, after the BIOS executes Power-On Self Test, it executes the first-stage bootloader, which is a compact 512-byte program that resides in the master boot record (MBR).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] Running in 16-bit real mode at address 0x7C00, it locates the second-stage bootloader.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] Its primary challenge lies in accomplishing these tasks within strict size constraints while handling potential hardware failures.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] The bootloader must navigate disk structures, often implementing FAT file system support, and manage the delicate transition from the BIOS startup state to a stable environment for the next boot stage.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] Microsoft boot sectors, therefore, traditionally imposed certain restrictions on the boot process.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] For example, the boot file had to be located at a fixed position in the root directory of the file system and stored within consecutive sectors, conditions taken care of by the `SYS` command and slightly relaxed in later versions of DOS.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] When Microsoft added logical block addressing (LBA) and FAT32 support, they switched to a boot loader reaching over *two* physical sectors, using 386 instructions for size reasons.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] At the same time, other vendors managed to squeeze much more functionality into a single boot sector without relaxing the original constraints on only minimal available memory (32 KiB) and processor support (8088/8086).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] For example, DR-DOS boot sectors are able to locate the boot file in the FAT12, FAT16 and FAT32 file systems, and load it into memory as a whole via CHS or LBA, even if the file is not stored in a fixed location and in consecutive sectors.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] In x86 computers, second-stage bootloaders, such as PBR, operate without the strict 512-byte limitation of their first-stage counterparts.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] They execute in a more sophisticated environment, typically ranging from 8KB to several megabytes in size.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] This expanded space allows implementation of complex features such as filesystem support, runtime configuration, and bootloader menu interfaces.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] The second-stage boot loader does not need drivers for its own operation, but may instead use generic storage access methods provided by system firmware such as the BIOS, though typically with restricted hardware functionality and lower performance.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] In x86 computers, third-stage bootloaders include IO.SYS, NTLDR, BOOTMGR, and GRUB.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] UEFI (except for CSM boot) does not rely on boot sectors; it directly loads the next-stage bootloader (such as BOOTMGR and GRUB2) from the EFI System Partition.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] At the completion of the operation, the system stores the I/O address in the halfword at location 2 and loads the PSW from location 0.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] The operating systems for S/360 through z/Architecture reside on direct access storage devices (DASDs), e.g., disk, drum.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] For these devices, *Read IPL* does a seek to cylinder 000016, head 000016, and orients to record 0116.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] For all supported operating systems, record 0116 contains a *Read Data* CCW to read a *bootstrap record* and a *Transfer In Channel* (TIC) CCW to the bootstrap.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] The channel program in the bootstrap reads the IPL program text into location 0, beginning with a PSW pointing to the first IPL program text instruction.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] For OS/360 the IPL program does some initialization, relocates itself, locates the *Nucleus*, loads the nucleus and transfers to the *Nucleus Initialization Program* (NIP) at the end of the Nucleus.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/bootloader] After these parts have been transferred, the operating system takes over the control of the booting process.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] U-Boot is both a first-stage and second-stage bootloader.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] It is loaded by the system's ROM (e.g. on-chip ROM of an ARM CPU) from a supported boot device, such as an SD card, SATA drive, NOR flash (e.g. using SPI or I²C), or NAND flash.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] If there are size constraints, U-Boot may be split into two stages: the platform would load a small SPL (Secondary Program Loader), which is a stripped-down version of U-Boot, and the SPL would do some initial hardware configuration (e.g.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] Regardless of whether the SPL is used, U-Boot performs both first-stage (e.g., configuring memory controller, SDRAM, mainboard and other I/O devices) and second-stage booting (e.g., loading OS kernel and other related files from storage device).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] U-Boot implements a subset of the UEFI specification as defined in the Embedded Base Boot Requirements (EBBR) specification.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] UEFI binaries like GRUB or the Linux kernel can be booted via the boot manager or from the command-line interface.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] U-Boot runs a command-line interface on a console or a serial port.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] Using the CLI, users can load and boot a kernel, possibly changing parameters from the default.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] Because U-Boot's commands are fairly low-level, it takes several steps to boot a kernel, but this also makes U-Boot more flexible than other bootloaders, since the same commands can be used for more general tasks.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] It's even possible to upgrade U-Boot using U-Boot, simply by reading the new bootloader from somewhere (local storage, or from the serial port or network) into memory, and writing that data to persistent storage where the bootloader belongs.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] U-Boot has support for USB, so it can use a USB keyboard to operate the console (in addition to input from the serial port), and it can access and boot from USB Mass Storage devices such as SD card readers.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] U-Boot boots an operating system by reading the kernel and any other required data (e.g. device tree, ramdisk image or boot image) into memory, and then executing the kernel with the appropriate arguments.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] U-Boot's commands are actually generalized commands which can be used to read or write any arbitrary data.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] (Note: These are boot sources from which U-Boot is capable of loading data (e.g. a kernel or ramdisk image) into memory.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] On some embedded device implementations, the CPU or SoC will locate and load the bootloader (such as Das U-Boot) from the boot partition (such as ext4 or FAT filesystems) directly.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] U-Boot does not need to be able to read a filesystem for the kernel to use it as a root filesystem or initial ramdisk; U-Boot simply provides an appropriate parameter to the kernel, and/or copies the data to memory without understanding its contents.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] However, U-Boot can also read from (and in some cases, write to) filesystems.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] This way, rather than requiring the data that U-Boot will load to be stored at a fixed location on the storage device, U-Boot can read the filesystem to search for and load the kernel, device tree, etc., by pathname.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] The project started as a 8xx PowerPC bootloader called **8xxROM** written by Magnus Damm.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] In October 1999 Wolfgang Denk moved the project to SourceForge.net and renamed it to **PPCBoot**, because SF.net did not allow project names starting with digits.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] Version 0.4.1 of PPCBoot was first publicly released 19 July 2000.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] In 2002 a previous version of the source code was briefly forked into a product called **ARMBoot**, but was merged back into the PPCBoot project shortly thereafter.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] This marked the last release under the PPCBoot name, as it was renamed to reflect its ability to work on other architectures besides the PPC ISA.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] PPCBoot−2.0.0 became **U−Boot−0.1.0** in November 2002, expanded to work on the x86 processor architecture.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] Additional architecture capabilities were added in the following months: MIPS32 in March 2003, MIPS64 in April, Nios II in October, ColdFire in December, and MicroBlaze in April 2004.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] The May 2004 release of U-Boot-1.1.2 worked on the products of 216 board manufacturers across the various architectures.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] The current name **Das U-Boot** adds a German definite article, to create a bilingual pun on the classic 1981 German submarine film *Das Boot*, which takes place on a World War II German U-boat .
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] It is free software released under the terms of the GNU General Public License.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] It can be built on an x86 PC for any of its intended architectures using a cross development GNU toolchain, for example crosstool, the Embedded Linux Development Kit (ELDK) or OSELAS.Toolchain.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] In 2025, multiple vulnerabilities discovered in 2024 have been disclosed in U-Boot.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] Abusing the filesystem support feature (ext4, SquashFS) of U-Boot by manually modifying filesystem data structures, an attacker can cause an integer overflow, a stack overflow or a heap overflow.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] As a result, an attacker can perform an arbitrary code execution and bypass the boot chain of trust.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/das-u-boot] These issues are mitigated by the version v2025.01-rc1.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] An **embedded system** is a specialized computer system—a combination of a computer processor, computer memory, and input/output peripheral devices—that has a dedicated function within a larger mechanical or electronic system.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] It is embedded as part of a complete device, often including electrical or electronic hardware and mechanical parts.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Embedded systems control many devices in common use.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] In 2009, it was estimated that 98% of all microprocessors manufactured were used in embedded systems.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Because an embedded system typically controls physical operations of the machine that it is embedded within, it often has real-time computing constraints.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Modern embedded systems are often based on microcontrollers (i.e., microprocessors with integrated memory and peripheral interfaces), but ordinary microprocessors (using external chips for memory and peripheral interface circuits) are also common, especially in more complex systems.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] In either case, the processor(s) used may be types ranging from general purpose to those specialized in a certain class of computations, or even custom designed for the application at hand.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] A common standard class of dedicated processors is the digital signal processor (DSP).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Since the embedded system is dedicated to specific tasks, design engineers can optimize it to reduce the size and cost of the product and increase its reliability and performance.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are mass-produced, benefiting from economies of scale.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Embedded systems range in size from portable personal devices such as digital watches and MP3 players to bigger machines like home appliances, industrial assembly lines, robots, transport vehicles, traffic light controllers, and medical imaging systems.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Often they constitute subsystems of other machines like avionics in aircraft and astrionics in spacecraft.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Large installations like factories, pipelines, and electrical grids rely on multiple embedded systems networked together.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Generalized through software customization, embedded systems such as programmable logic controllers frequently comprise their functional units.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] The origins of the microprocessor and the microcontroller can be traced back to the MOS integrated circuit, which is an integrated circuit chip fabricated from MOSFETs (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors) and was developed in the early 1960s.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] By 1964, MOS chips had reached higher transistor density and lower manufacturing costs than bipolar chips.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] MOS chips further increased in complexity at a rate predicted by Moore's law, leading to large-scale integration (LSI) with hundreds of transistors on a single MOS chip by the late 1960s.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] The application of MOS LSI chips to computing was the basis for the first microprocessors, as engineers began recognizing that a complete computer processor system could be contained on several MOS LSI chips.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] The first multi-chip microprocessors, the Four-Phase Systems AL1 in 1969 and the Garrett AiResearch MP944 in 1970, were developed with multiple MOS LSI chips.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] The first single-chip microprocessor was the Intel 4004, released in 1971.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] It was developed by Federico Faggin, using his silicon-gate MOS technology, along with Intel engineers Marcian Hoff and Stan Mazor, and Busicom engineer Masatoshi Shima.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] One of the first recognizably modern embedded systems was the Apollo Guidance Computer, developed ca.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] 1965 by Charles Stark Draper at the MIT Instrumentation Laboratory.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] At the project's inception, the Apollo guidance computer was considered the riskiest item in the Apollo project as it employed the then newly developed monolithic integrated circuits to reduce the computer's size and weight.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] An early mass-produced embedded system was the Autonetics D-17 guidance computer for the Minuteman missile, released in 1961.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] When the Minuteman II went into production in 1966, the D-17 was replaced with a new computer that represented the first high-volume use of integrated circuits.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Since these early applications in the 1960s, embedded systems have come down in price and there has been a dramatic rise in processing power and functionality.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] An early microprocessor, the Intel 4004 (released in 1971), was designed for calculators and other small systems but still required external memory and support chips.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] By the early 1980s, memory, input and output system components had been integrated into the same chip as the processor, forming a microcontroller.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Microcontrollers find applications where a general-purpose computer would be too costly.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] As the cost of microprocessors and microcontrollers fell, the prevalence of embedded systems increased.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] A comparatively low-cost microcontroller may be programmed to fulfill the same role as a large number of separate components.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] With microcontrollers, it became feasible to replace, even in consumer products, expensive knob-based analog components such as potentiometers and variable capacitors with up/down buttons or knobs read out by a microprocessor.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Although in this context an embedded system is usually more complex than a traditional solution, most of the complexity is contained within the microcontroller itself.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Very few additional components may be needed and most of the design effort is in the software.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Software prototype and test can be quicker compared with the design and construction of a new circuit not using an embedded processor.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Embedded systems are commonly found in consumer, industrial, automotive, home appliances, medical, telecommunication, commercial, aerospace and military applications.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Telecommunications systems employ numerous embedded systems from telephone switches for the network to cell phones at the end user.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Computer networking uses dedicated routers and network bridges to route data.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Consumer electronics include MP3 players, television sets, mobile phones, video game consoles, digital cameras, GPS receivers, and printers.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Household appliances, such as microwave ovens, washing machines and dishwashers, include embedded systems to provide flexibility, efficiency and features.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Advanced heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) systems use networked thermostats to more accurately and efficiently control temperature that can change by time of day and season.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Home automation uses wired and wireless networking that can be used to control lights, climate, security, audio/visual, surveillance, etc., all of which use embedded devices for sensing and controlling.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Transportation systems from flight to automobiles increasingly use embedded systems.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] New airplanes contain advanced avionics such as inertial guidance systems and GPS receivers that also have considerable safety requirements.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Spacecraft rely on astrionics systems for trajectory correction.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Various electric motors — brushless DC motors, induction motors and DC motors — use electronic motor controllers.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Automobiles, electric vehicles, and hybrid vehicles increasingly use embedded systems to maximize efficiency and reduce pollution.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Other automotive safety systems using embedded systems include anti-lock braking system (ABS), electronic stability control (ESC/ESP), traction control (TCS) and automatic four-wheel drive.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Medical equipment uses embedded systems for monitoring, and various medical imaging (positron emission tomography (PET), single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT), computed tomography (CT), and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) for non-invasive internal inspections.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Embedded systems within medical equipment are often powered by industrial computers.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Embedded systems are used for safety-critical systems in aerospace and defense industries.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Unless connected to wired or wireless networks via on-chip 3G cellular or other methods for IoT monitoring and control purposes, these systems can be isolated from hacking and thus be more secure.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] For fire safety, the systems can be designed to have a greater ability to handle higher temperatures and continue to operate.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] In dealing with security, the embedded systems can be self-sufficient and be able to deal with cut electrical and communication systems.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Miniature wireless devices called motes are networked wireless sensors.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] These motes are completely self-contained and will typically run off a battery source for years before the batteries need to be changed or charged.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Embedded systems are designed to perform a specific task, in contrast with general-purpose computers designed for multiple tasks.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Some have real-time performance constraints that must be met, for reasons such as safety and usability; others may have low or no performance requirements, allowing the system hardware to be simplified to reduce costs.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Embedded systems are not always standalone devices.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Many embedded systems are a small part within a larger device that serves a more general purpose.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] For example, the Gibson Robot Guitar features an embedded system for tuning the strings, but the overall purpose of the Robot Guitar is to play music.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Similarly, an embedded system in an automobile provides a specific function as a subsystem of the car itself.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] The program instructions written for embedded systems are referred to as firmware, and are stored in read-only memory or flash memory chips.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] They run with limited computer hardware resources: little memory, small or non-existent keyboard or screen.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Embedded systems range from no user interface at all, in systems dedicated to one task, to complex graphical user interfaces that resemble modern computer desktop operating systems.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Simple embedded devices use buttons, light-emitting diodes (LED), graphic or character liquid-crystal displays (LCD) with a simple menu system.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] More sophisticated devices that use a graphical screen with touch sensing or screen-edge soft keys provide flexibility while minimizing space used: the meaning of the buttons can change with the screen, and selection involves the natural behavior of pointing at what is desired.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Some systems provide user interface remotely with the help of a serial (e.g.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] This approach extends the capabilities of the embedded system, avoids the cost of a display, simplifies the board support package (BSP) and allows designers to build a rich user interface on the PC.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] A good example of this is the combination of an embedded HTTP server running on an embedded device (such as an IP camera or a network router).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] The user interface is displayed in a web browser on a PC connected to the device.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Examples of properties of typical embedded computers when compared with general-purpose counterparts are low power consumption, small size, rugged operating ranges, and low per-unit cost.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] This comes at the expense of limited processing resources.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Numerous microcontrollers have been developed for embedded systems use.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] General-purpose microprocessors are also used in embedded systems, but generally require more support circuitry than microcontrollers.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] PC/104 and PC/104+ are examples of standards for ready-made computer boards intended for small, low-volume embedded and ruggedized systems.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] These are mostly x86-based and often physically small compared to a standard PC, although still large compared to most simple (8/16-bit) embedded systems.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] They may use a standard operating system such as Linux or NetBSD or an embedded real-time operating system (RTOS) such as MicroC/OS-II, QNX or VxWorks.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] In certain applications, where small size or power efficiency are not primary concerns, the components used may be compatible with those used in general-purpose x86 personal computers.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Boards such as the VIA EPIA range help to bridge the gap by being PC-compatible but highly integrated, physically smaller or have other attributes making them attractive to embedded engineers.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] The advantage of this approach is that low-cost commodity components may be used along with the same software development tools used for general software development.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Systems built in this way are still regarded as embedded since they are integrated into larger devices and fulfill a single role.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Examples of devices that may adopt this approach are automated teller machines (ATM) and arcade machines, which contain code specific to the application.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] However, most ready-made embedded systems boards are not PC-centered and do not use the ISA or PCI buses.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] When a system-on-a-chip processor is involved, there may be little benefit to having a standardized bus connecting discrete components, and the environment for both hardware and software tools may be very different.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] One common design style uses a small system module, perhaps the size of a business card, holding high density BGA chips such as an ARM-based system-on-a-chip processor and peripherals, external flash memory for storage, and DRAM for runtime memory.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] The module vendor will usually provide boot software and make sure there is a selection of operating systems, usually including Linux and some real-time choices.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] These modules can be manufactured in high volume, by organizations familiar with their specialized testing issues and combined with much lower volume custom mainboards with application-specific external peripherals.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Prominent examples of this approach include Arduino and Raspberry Pi.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] A system on a chip (SoC) contains a complete system - consisting of multiple processors, multipliers, caches, even different types of memory and commonly various peripherals like interfaces for wired or wireless communication on a single chip.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Often graphics processing units (GPU) and DSPs are included such chips.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] SoCs can be implemented as an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) or using a field-programmable gate array (FPGA), which typically can be reconfigured.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] ASIC implementations are common for very-high-volume embedded systems like mobile phones and smartphones.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] ASIC or FPGA implementations may be used for not-so-high-volume embedded systems with special needs in terms of signal processing performance, interfaces and reliability, like in avionics.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] As with other software, embedded system designers use compilers, assemblers, and debuggers to develop embedded system software.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Embedded software often requires a variety of development tools, including programming languages such as C++, Rust, or Python, and frameworks like Qt for graphical interfaces.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] These tools enable developers to create efficient, scalable, and feature-rich applications tailored to the specific requirements of embedded systems.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] The choice of tools is driven by factors such as real-time performance, integration with hardware, or energy efficiency.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] As the complexity of embedded systems grows, higher-level tools and operating systems are migrating into machinery where it makes sense.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] For example, cellphones, personal digital assistants and other consumer computers often need significant software that is purchased or provided by a person other than the manufacturer of the electronics.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] In these systems, an open programming environment such as Linux, NetBSD, FreeBSD, OSGi or Embedded Java is required so that the third-party software provider can sell to a large market.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Embedded debugging may be performed at different levels, depending on the facilities available.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Unless restricted to external debugging, the programmer can typically load and run software through the tools, view the code running in the processor, and start or stop its operation.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] The view of the code may be as high-level programming language, assembly code or a mixture of both.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Real-time operating systems often support tracing of operating system events.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] A graphical view is presented by a host PC tool, based on a recording of the system behavior.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] The trace recording can be performed in software, by the RTOS, or by special tracing hardware.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] RTOS tracing allows developers to understand timing and performance issues of the software system and gives a good understanding of the high-level system behaviors.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Trace recording in embedded systems can be achieved using hardware or software solutions.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Software-based trace recording does not require specialized debugging hardware and can be used to record traces in deployed devices, but it can have an impact on CPU and RAM usage.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] One example of a software-based tracing method used in RTOS environments is the use of empty macros which are invoked by the operating system at strategic places in the code, and can be implemented to serve as hooks.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Embedded systems often reside in machines that are expected to run continuously for years without error, and in some cases, recover by themselves if an error occurs.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Therefore, the software is usually developed and tested more carefully than that for personal computers, and unreliable mechanical moving parts such as disk drives, switches or buttons are avoided.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] For high-volume systems such as mobile phones, minimizing cost is usually the primary design consideration.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Engineers typically select hardware that is just good enough to implement the necessary functions.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] For low-volume or prototype embedded systems, general-purpose computers may be adapted by limiting the programs or by replacing the operating system with an RTOS.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] In 1978 National Electrical Manufacturers Association released ICS 3-1978, a standard for programmable microcontrollers, including almost any computer-based controllers, such as single-board computers, numerical, and event-based controllers.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] There are several different types of software architecture in common use.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] In this design, the software simply has a loop which monitors the input devices.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] The loop calls subroutines, each of which manages a part of the hardware or software.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Hence it is called a simple control loop or programmed input-output.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are predominantly controlled by interrupts.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] This means that tasks performed by the system are triggered by different kinds of events; an interrupt could be generated, for example, by a timer at a predefined interval, or by a serial port controller receiving data.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] This architecture is used if event handlers need low latency, and the event handlers are short and simple.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] These systems run a simple task in a main loop also, but this task is not very sensitive to unexpected delays.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Sometimes the interrupt handler will add longer tasks to a queue structure.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Later, after the interrupt handler has finished, these tasks are executed by the main loop.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] This method brings the system close to a multitasking kernel with discrete processes.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Cooperative multitasking is very similar to the simple control loop scheme, except that the loop is hidden in an API.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] The programmer defines a series of tasks, and each task gets its own environment to run in.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] When a task is idle, it calls an idle routine, which passes control to another task.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] The advantages and disadvantages are similar to those of the control loop, except that adding new software is easier, by simply writing a new task, or adding to the queue.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] In this type of system, a low-level piece of code switches between tasks or threads based on a timer that invokes an interrupt.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] This is the level at which the system is generally considered to have an operating system kernel.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Depending on how much functionality is required, it introduces more or less of the complexities associated with managing multiple tasks running conceptually in parallel.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Because of these complexities, it is common for organizations to use an off-the-shelf RTOS, allowing the application programmers to concentrate on device functionality rather than operating system services.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] The choice to include an RTOS brings in its own issues, however, as the selection must be made prior to starting the application development process.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] This timing forces developers to choose the embedded operating system for their device based on current requirements and so restricts future options to a large extent.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] These trends are leading to the uptake of embedded middleware in addition to an RTOS.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] A microkernel allocates memory and switches the CPU to different threads of execution.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] User-mode processes implement major functions such as file systems, network interfaces, etc.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Exokernels communicate efficiently by normal subroutine calls.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] The hardware and all the software in the system are available to and extensible by application programmers.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] A monolithic kernel is a relatively large kernel with sophisticated capabilities adapted to suit an embedded environment.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] This gives programmers an environment similar to a desktop operating system like Linux or Microsoft Windows, and is therefore very productive for development.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] On the downside, it requires considerably more hardware resources, is often more expensive, and, because of the complexity of these kernels, can be less predictable and reliable.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Common examples of embedded monolithic kernels are embedded Linux, VXWorks and Windows CE.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] Despite the increased cost in hardware, this type of embedded system is increasing in popularity, especially on the more powerful embedded devices such as wireless routers and GPS navigation systems.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] In addition to the core operating system, many embedded systems have additional upper-layer software components.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] These components include networking protocol stacks like CAN, TCP/IP, FTP, HTTP, and HTTPS, and storage capabilities like FAT and flash memory management systems.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] If the embedded device has audio and video capabilities, then the appropriate drivers and codecs will be present in the system.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] In the case of the monolithic kernels, many of these software layers may be included in the kernel.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] In the RTOS category, the availability of additional software components depends on the commercial offering.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/embedded-system] In the automotive sector, AUTOSAR is a standard architecture for embedded software.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] In computing, **firmware** (**FW**) is software that provides low-level control of computer hardware.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] For a relatively simple device, firmware may perform all control, monitoring and data manipulation functionality.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] For a more complex device, firmware may provide only relatively low-level control as well as hardware abstraction to higher-level software such as an operating system.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Firmware is found in a wide range of computing devices, including personal computers, smartphones, home appliances, vehicles, computer peripherals and in many of the integrated circuits inside each of these larger systems.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Firmware is stored in non-volatile memory – either read-only memory (ROM) or programmable memory such as EPROM, EEPROM, or flash.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Changing a device's firmware stored in ROM requires physically replacing the memory chip or the device itself.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Programmable firmware memory can be reprogrammed via a procedure sometimes called *flashing*.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Common reasons for changing firmware include fixing bugs and adding features.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Ascher Opler used the term *firmware* in a 1967 *Datamation* article, as an intermediary term between *hardware* and *software*.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Opler projected that fourth-generation computer systems would have a writable control store (a small specialized high-speed memory) into which microcode firmware would be loaded.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Many software functions would be moved to microcode, and instruction sets could be customized, with different firmware loaded for different instruction sets.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] As computers began to increase in complexity, it became clear that various programs needed to first be initiated and run to provide a consistent environment necessary for running more complex programs at the user's discretion.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] This required programming the computer to run those programs automatically.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Furthermore, as companies, universities, and marketers wanted to sell computers to laypeople with little technical knowledge, greater automation became necessary to allow a layperson to easily run programs for practical purposes.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] This gave rise to a kind of software that a user would not consciously run, and it led to software that a lay user would not even know about.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] As originally used, firmware contrasted with hardware (the CPU itself) and software (normal instructions executing on a CPU).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] It was not composed of CPU machine instructions, but of lower-level microcode involved in the implementation of machine instructions.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] It existed on the boundary between hardware and software; thus the name *firmware*.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] In some respects, the various firmware components are as important as the operating system in a working computer.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] However, unlike most modern operating systems, firmware rarely has a well-evolved automatic mechanism of updating itself to fix any functionality issues detected after shipping the unit.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] A computer's firmware may be manually updated by a user via a small utility program.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] In contrast, firmware in mass storage devices (hard-disk drives, optical disc drives, flash memory storage e.g., solid state drive) is less frequently updated, even when flash memory (rather than ROM, EEPROM) storage is used for the firmware.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Most computer peripherals are themselves special-purpose computers.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Devices such as printers, scanners, webcams, and USB flash drives have internally-stored firmware; some devices may also permit field upgrading of their firmware.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] For modern, simpler devices, such as USB keyboards, USB mouses and USB sound cards, the trend is to store the firmware in on-chip memory in the device's microcontroller, as opposed to storing it in a separate EEPROM chip.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Consumer products like digital cameras and portable music players support firmware upgrades.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] In digital cameras, firmware upgrades address bugs in the operation, along with adding new functions to the camera's operation.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Some companies use firmware updates to add new playable file formats (codecs).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Other features that may change with firmware updates include the user interface or even the battery life.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Since 1996, most automobiles have employed an on-board computer and various sensors to detect mechanical problems.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] As of 2010, modern vehicles also employ computer-controlled anti-lock braking systems (ABS) and computer-operated transmission control units (TCUs).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] The driver can also get in-dash information while driving in this manner, such as real-time fuel economy and tire pressure readings.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Local dealers can update most vehicle firmware.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Sometimes, third parties develop an unofficial new or modified ("aftermarket") version of firmware to provide new features or to unlock hidden functionality; this is referred to as custom firmware.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] An example is Rockbox as a firmware replacement for portable media players.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] There are many homebrew projects for various devices, which often unlock general-purpose computing functionality in previously limited devices (e.g., running Doom on iPods).
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Firmware hacks usually take advantage of the firmware update facility on many devices to install or run themselves.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Some, however, must resort to exploits to run, because the manufacturer has attempted to lock the hardware to stop it from running unlicensed code.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Although the Kaspersky Lab report did not explicitly claim that this group is part of the United States National Security Agency (NSA), evidence obtained from the code of various Equation Group software suggests that they are part of the NSA.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Researchers from the Kaspersky Lab categorized the undertakings by Equation Group as the most advanced hacking operation ever uncovered, also documenting around 500 infections caused by the Equation Group in at least 42 countries.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Mark Shuttleworth, the founder of the company Canonical, which created the Ubuntu Linux distribution, has described proprietary firmware as a security risk, saying that "firmware on your device is the NSA's best friend" and calling firmware "a trojan horse of monumental proportions".
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] As a potential solution to this problem, he has called for declarative firmware, which would describe "hardware linkage and dependencies" and "should not include executable code".
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Firmware should be open-source so that the code can be checked and verified.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Custom firmware hacks have also focused on injecting malware into devices such as smartphones or USB devices.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] One such smartphone injection was demonstrated on the Symbian OS at MalCon, a hacker convention.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] A USB device firmware hack called BadUSB was presented at the Black Hat USA 2014 conference, demonstrating how a USB flash drive microcontroller can be reprogrammed to spoof various other device types to take control of a computer, exfiltrate data, or spy on the user.
[src:u-boot-bootloader/firmware] Other security researchers have worked further on how to exploit the principles behind BadUSB, releasing at the same time the source code of hacking tools that can be used to modify the behavior of different USB devices.
